    <mj-section>
      <mj-column>
        <mj-image alt="" src="https://github.com/mjcampagna/mjml/blob/main/newsletters/202310/JH_20230924_MattKatrinaWedding_FINALS-49.jpg?raw=true" />
        <mj-text css-class="article">
          <p>Hi [Name,fallback=Friend],</p>
          <p>This newsletter is months overdue, but I&#8217;ve been quite busy. I got married!</p>

          <p>And now I am getting back up to speed. It&#8217;s actually very nice for things to be getting back to normal. More normal, please?</p>

          <p>No Backlight updates this time around, but I think it's a good time to talk about Kookaburra, and I do have two new videos on the blog.</p>

          <p>The first demonstrates how to <a href="https://blog.theturninggate.net/2023/10/02/using-kookaburra-templates-in-backlight-5/">replace the default Pangolin templates with Kookaburra</a>.</p>
          
          The second, <a href="https://blog.theturninggate.net/2023/10/02/writing-essays-in-kookaburra/">shows off the improved essay features in Kookburra</a>.</p>

          <p>One of the roadblocks to getting these videos done, my video suite crapped out on me at some point, and I needed to find time to figure out how to use Final Cut Pro at a basic level, rebuild the intro frames, etc. That's done now!</p>

          <p>Enough rattling. Let&#8217;s do this newsletter!</p>
        </mj-text>        
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <mj-section>
      <mj-column>
        <mj-image alt="Backlight 5.x.x Hero" src="https://github.com/mjcampagna/mjml/blob/main/newsletters/202310/20230719-162626-mc-2342.jpg?raw=true" />
        <mj-text css-class="article">
          <h2>Soaring with Backlight 5 + Kookaburra</h2>
          <p>Backlight is at version 5.3.2, released July 18. Our next update is in-progress.</p>

          <p>In the meantime, Backlight 5 and Kookaburra had their one-year anniversary in August. We passed quietly by the occassion, busy as we&#8217;ve been, but it makes for good justification to snapshot Kookaburra in its current form and reflect upon it.</p>

          <p>The Kookaburra series design modules were, are, and will remain for some time to come works in progress. I have macheted my way through enough of <a href="https://discourse.theturninggate.net/t/kookaburra-roadmap/2313/3">the roadmap</a>, though, I think its fair to drum up some hype.</p>

          <p>Kookaburra is not yet a one-to-one replacement for Pangolin, but there are compelling reasons to use it right now. I think it&#8217;s definitely the right choice for the majority of new sites built on Backlight; for existing sites, migration is worth thinking about, depending on your use case.</p>

          <p>The most significant caveats are the Cart and Client Response add-ons, which remain Pangolin exclusive for the time being. If your site is structured such that you can sequester your cart or client areas away from your portfolio, then consider a Kookaburra/Pangolin hybrid! I understand this may not be viable for all users, though.</p>

          <p>But think about it, because ...</p>
        </mj-text>  
        <mj-image alt="Backlight 5.3.2 Lighthouse Scores" src="https://github.com/mjcampagna/mjml/blob/main/newsletters/202310/Backlight-5-Album-Lighthouse-Audit-20230930.png?raw=true" />
        <mj-text css-class="article">
          <p>We&#8217;ve aced our Lighthouse scores! </p>

          <p>These results are from an audit performed on September 30, 2023, with Backlight 5.3.2. The audited album is on my personal website, using Kookaburra Album, and contains more than 200 images. Those colorful dots on the left-hand side? That&#8217;s confetti popping off in celebration of Kookaburra&#8217;s awesomeness!</p>

          <p>So, that&#8217;s four compelling reasons to be using Kookaburra, high marks in all of performance, accessibility, best practices, and search engine optimization.</p>

          <p>The 5.3.0 update brought one of my favorite things in Kookaburra, the new suite of essay features! Essays were first introduced to Pangolin in Backlight 4, but Kookaburra brings major enhances, all the while screaming, "Essay anywhere!" Check it out in our latest video, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kj5RqHwCk08" target="_blank">Essays in Kookaburra, in Backlight 5</a>.</p>

          <p>Kookaburra also makes important strides for keyboard users, built from the ground up for <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/quickref/#keyboard-accessible" target="_blank">keyboard accessibility</a> and 100% navigable using only the keyboard. We are making best efforts to be compliant with the <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/standards-guidelines/wcag/" target="_blank">Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) international standard</a>, that standard or some derivative thereof now having been codified into law <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_Content_Accessibility_Guidelines#WCAG_referenced_by_law" target="_blank">in numerous countries</a>, including the United States, United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, and Israel, and countries within the European Union. Keyboard accessibility is covered under operability <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/quickref/#keyboard-accessible" target="_blank">Guideline 2.1</a> in the WCAG specification.</p>

          <p>Kookaburra endeavors to put you on good footing for accessibility compliance, helping to ensure the best possible user experience for your visitors, and exceptional longevity for your website.</p>

          <p>By this point, I hope you're keen to give Kookaburra a try for yourself, and our new video, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tjiWJ36mudg" target="_blank">Using Kookaburra Templates in Backlight 5</a>, will help you to do that.</p>

          <p>If you'd like to read more about Kookaburra's advantages, and its caveats, <a href="https://blog.theturninggate.net/2023/10/02/using-kookaburra-templates-in-backlight-5/" target="_blank">find a longer version of this article on our blog</a>.
        </mj-text>        
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <mj-section>
      <mj-column>
        <mj-image alt="Backlight 5.x.x Hero" src="https://github.com/mjcampagna/mjml/blob/main/newsletters/202310/BricolageGrotesque.jpg?raw=true" />
        <mj-text css-class="article">
          <h2>New typeface, "Bricolage Grotesque"</h2>
          <p><a href="https://ateliertriay.github.io/bricolage/">Bricolage Grotesque</a> is a new open source typeface from the creators of Marvin Visions, the typeface that I use (and adore!) for Backlight's logo.</p>
          <p>Bricolage Grotesque is described as "a free and open source variable font with French attitude and British mannerisms across 3 axis: weight, width &amp; optical size."</p>
          <p>Check it out, give it a download, or <a href="https://fonts.google.com/specimen/Bricolage+Grotesque">bookmark it on Google Fonts</a>.</p>
          <p>And remember, a few months ago we shared an updated tutorial on <a href="https://backlight.me/docs/google-fonts">Using Google Fonts in Backlight</a>! Though it's not just for Google Fonts; the tutorial will show you how to use font files from anywhere with Backlight.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

